    pearls: ["ALWAYS check the PDMP before prescribing any controlled substance: it identifies multi-provider prescribing, dose escalation, concurrent dangerous combinations (opioid + benzodiazepine), and early refill patterns; document the PDMP review in every chart note","Concurrent opioid and benzodiazepine prescribing is the HIGHEST RISK combination for fatal overdose: both suppress breathing through different mechanisms; FDA Black Box Warning; if both are medically necessary, use lowest effective doses with enhanced monitoring","MME calculation is ESSENTIAL for safe opioid prescribing: common conversions include oxycodone x 1.5, hydromorphone x 4, oral morphine x 1 (reference standard); CDC cautions at >=50 MME/day and strongly recommends avoiding >=90 MME/day","NEVER initiate extended-release/long-acting (ER/LA) opioids in opioid-naive patients: start with immediate-release formulations to establish effective dose and tolerance; ER/LA opioids in opioid-naive patients carry highest risk of respiratory depression and death","Naloxone should be co-prescribed to ALL patients on chronic opioids: educate patient AND household members on recognizing overdose (respiratory rate <12, pinpoint pupils, unresponsive) and administering intranasal naloxone; naloxone duration (30-90 min) is shorter than most opioids -- patient must be monitored after reversal","Functional improvement, NOT pain score alone, should guide opioid therapy decisions: use validated tools (PEG scale) measuring pain, enjoyment of life, and general activity; if function is not improving despite dose escalation, opioids are likely not the appropriate therapy"],
