    pearls: ["Lemierre syndrome is the 'FORGOTTEN DISEASE' -- consider it in any previously healthy young person (16-25 years) with recent pharyngitis who develops HIGH FEVER, RIGORS, NECK PAIN, and PULMONARY INFILTRATES; the patient appears 'too sick for a sore throat'","Fusobacterium necrophorum is the classic causative organism: it is an ANAEROBIC gram-negative rod that requires ANAEROBIC culture conditions and extended incubation (3-7 days); alert the microbiology lab to hold anaerobic cultures longer than standard protocols","Septic PULMONARY EMBOLI are present in 80-100% of cases: look for bilateral peripheral nodular infiltrates with CAVITATION on chest CT; these may mimic metastatic disease or tuberculosis on initial imaging","Metronidazole is the drug of choice for Fusobacterium: excellent anaerobic bactericidal activity and tissue penetration; combine with a broad-spectrum beta-lactam (ampicillin-sulbactam, piperacillin-tazobactam) for empiric polymicrobial coverage; total treatment duration 4-6 weeks","Fusobacterium is RESISTANT to macrolides (azithromycin, clarithromycin): if a patient with pharyngitis was treated with azithromycin and is now presenting with persistent fever, neck pain, and pulmonary symptoms, consider Lemierre syndrome -- azithromycin would not have treated Fusobacterium","The role of ANTICOAGULATION in Lemierre syndrome is CONTROVERSIAL: no RCT data exists; some experts recommend anticoagulation for extensive IJV thrombosis or embolic progression; most experts agree that antibiotics and source control are the cornerstones of treatment"],
